<p class="">No, Sir. If I may say so, that question does not arise at all. It often happens that information has to be obtained from outside bodies, whether private companies, public companies or the nationalised boards, as the basis of information given in this House, and it is usual in those circumstances for the Minister to use the phrase, "I am informed that." As a matter of fact, I do not think that in general any difficulty arises in relying on this information.</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
